3/38007358-48714ad0-3273-11e8-8115-8acb0efabb96.gif)\r\n\r\n\r\n## Upd1: What is sent in request ✈️ \r\n\r\nIn request plain order indices are sent. So if you select options: 1st and 4th, you'll see in request form data:\r\n**works[]** 0\r\n**works[]** 3\r\n\r\n## Upd2: Where the problem is 💩 \r\n\r\n• Here's that little naughty piece of  code, that magically converts `[\"0\",\"3\"] to [\"1\"=>\"3\"]`:\r\nhttps://github.com/bolt/bolt/blob/3.4/src/Storage/Entity/Content.php#L60\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2145313/38008502-49517532-3279-11e8-8221-870c460f4c20.png)\r\n\r\n\r\n### • [array_filter](https://secure.php.net/manual/en/function.array-filter.php)\r\n> Iterates over each value in the array passing them to the callback function. If the callback function returns true, the current value from array is returned into the result array. Array keys are preserved.\r\n\r\n• so, if you don't pass a callback, all *falsy* values will be rejected\r\n```php\r\n$arr = [0, 1, 2, '0', '', null];\r\nprint_r(array_filter($arr));  // Will output: Array ( [1] => 1, [2] => 2 )\r\n```\r\n\r\n• then, if frontend sends `[0, 3]` in form, only `[1 => 3]` passes.\r\n\r\n• And after all it's dumped as `{\"1\":\"3\"}` to database.\r\n\r\nResume\r\n---\r\n1. **Array_filter** is a weak part. It rejects 0 option.\r\n2. Frontend sends incorrect keys. So it's a big bug, because if you rely on documentation ([defining-values-as-a-hash](https://docs.bolt.cm/3.4/fields/select#defining-values-as-a-hash)) people will assume that hash `{1: 'option1', 'anotheroption': 'option2'}` will work. But in fact - it won't.\r\n\r\n##### Another reproduction:\r\n- create a select key with values: \r\n```yml\r\nvalues:\r\n    1: opt1\r\n    2 : opt2\r\n    foo: opt3\r\n```\r\n- create a record, save it\r\n- change the order (1 ←→ 2).\r\n- 💥 you'll get another values.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n","score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bolt/bolt/issues/7410","repository_url":"https://a